# Email Validation Form with RFC Limitations Explained

Here's a comprehensive single-file solution:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
  <title>Email Validation — Regex vs Reality</title>
  <style>
    /* ── Reset & Base ── */
    *, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }

    body {
      font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, sans-serif;
      background: #0f172a;
      color: #e2e8f0;
      min-height: 100vh;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      padding: 2rem 1rem;
      gap: 2rem;
    }

    h1 {
      font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 4vw, 2rem);
      font-weight: 700;
      text-align: center;
      color: #f8fafc;
      letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    }

    h1 span { color: #38bdf8; }

    /* ── Card ── */
    .card {
      background: #1e293b;
      border: 1px solid #334155;
      border-radius: 1rem;
      padding: 2rem;
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 640px;
    }

    .card h2 {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
      color: #94a3b8;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      font-size: 0.8rem;
    }

    /* ── Form ── */
    .form-group { position: relative; margin-bottom: 1rem; }

    label {
      display: block;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      font-weight: 500;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
      color: #cbd5e1;
    }

    input[type="email"], input[type="text"] {
      width: 100%;
      padding: 0.75rem 2.75rem 0.75rem 1rem;
      background: #0f172a;
      border: 2px solid #334155;
      border-radius: 0.6rem;
      color: #f1f5f9;
      font-size: 1rem;
      outline: none;
      transition: border-color 0.25s ease, box-shadow 0.25s ease;
    }

    input:focus { border-color: #38bdf8; box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(56,189,248,0.15); }

    /* Feedback states */
    input.valid   { border-color: #22c55e; box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(34,197,94,0.15); }
    input.invalid { border-color: #ef4444; box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(239,68,68,0.15); }
    input.empty   { border-color: #334155; box-shadow: none; }

    /* Icon inside input */
    .icon {
      position: absolute;
      right: 0.85rem;
      top: 50%;
      transform: translateY(-50%);
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      pointer-events: none;
      transition: opacity 0.2s;
    }

    /* Offset icon for label */
    .form-group .icon { top: calc(50% + 0.9rem); }

    .hint {
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      margin-top: 0.4rem;
      min-height: 1.1em;
      transition: color 0.2s;
    }
    .hint.ok  { color: #4ade80; }
    .hint.err { color: #f87171; }
    .hint.neu { color: #64748b; }

    /* ── Test cases table ── */
    .test-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1fr auto auto;
      gap: 0.35rem 1rem;
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      align-items: center;
    }

    .test-grid .header {
      font-weight: 700;
      color: #94a3b8;
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      padding-bottom: 0.25rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid #334155;
    }

    .test-grid .email-cell {
      font-family: "Fira Code", "Cascadia Code", monospace;
      color: #e2e8f0;
      word-break: break-all;
    }

    .badge {
      display: inline-block;
      padding: 0.15rem 0.5rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      text-align: center;
      white-space: nowrap;
    }
    .badge.pass  { background: #14532d; color: #4ade80; }
    .badge.fail  { background: #450a0a; color: #f87171; }
    .badge.warn  { background: #422006; color: #fb923c; }
    .badge.valid { background: #0c4a6e; color: #38bdf8; }

    /* ── Limitation sections ── */
    .limitation-list {
      list-style: none;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.9rem;
    }

    .limitation-list li {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 2rem 1fr;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      align-items: start;
    }

    .lim-icon { font-size: 1.2rem; }

    .lim-body strong {
      display: block;
      color: #f1f5f9;
      font-size: 0.92rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.15rem;
    }

    .lim-body p {
      color: #94a3b8;
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
    }

    code {
      background: #0f172a;
      border: 1px solid #334155;
      border-radius: 0.3rem;
      padding: 0.05rem 0.35rem;
      font-family: "Fira Code", "Cascadia Code", monospace;
      font-size: 0.82em;
      color: #7dd3fc;
    }

    /* ── Alternatives ── */
    .alt-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(180px, 1fr));
      gap: 0.75rem;
    }

    .alt-card {
      background: #0f172a;
      border: 1px solid #334155;
      border-radius: 0.6rem;
      padding: 1rem;
    }

    .alt-card .alt-title {
      font-weight: 700;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      color: #38bdf8;
      margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
    }

    .alt-card .alt-lang {
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      color: #64748b;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
      font-family: monospace;
    }

    .alt-card p {
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      color: #94a3b8;
      line-height: 1.5;
    }

    .alt-card .pro  { color: #4ade80; font-size: 0.75rem; margin-top: 0.4rem; }
    .alt-card .con  { color: #f87171; font-size: 0.75rem; }

    /* ── RFC quote ── */
    blockquote {
      border-left: 3px solid #38bdf8;
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      background: #0f172a;
      border-radius: 0 0.4rem 0.4rem 0;
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      color: #94a3b8;
      font-style: italic;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    blockquote cite {
      display: block;
      margin-top: 0.4rem;
      font-style: normal;
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      color: #475569;
    }

    /* ── Regex display ── */
    .regex-box {
      background: #0f172a;
      border: 1px solid #334155;
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
      font-family: "Fira Code", "Cascadia Code", monospace;
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      color: #7dd3fc;
      word-break: break-all;
      line-height: 1.7;
    }

    .regex-box.simple { color: #86efac; }

    /* ── Divider ── */
    hr {
      border: none;
      border-top: 1px solid #1e293b;
      margin: 0.5rem 0;
    }

    /* ── Scrollable note ── */
    .scroll-note {
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      color: #475569;
      text-align: center;
      margin-top: -1rem;
    }

    /* ── Footer ── */
    footer {
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      color: #475569;
      text-align: center;
      max-width: 640px;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Email Validation<br/><span>Regex vs. RFC Reality</span></h1>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
       SECTION 1 — Live Validation Demo
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2>🔴 Live Regex Validation</h2>

    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="email-simple">Simple Regex <code>/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/</code></label>
      <input type="text" id="email-simple" placeholder="type an email…" autocomplete="off" />
      <span class="icon" id="icon-simple"></span>
      <p class="hint neu" id="hint-simple">Start typing to see feedback</p>
    </div>

    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="email-moderate">Moderate Regex <code>/^[\w._%+\-]+@[\w.\-]+\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}$/</code></label>
      <input type="text" id="email-moderate" placeholder="type an email…" autocomplete="off" />
      <span class="icon" id="icon-moderate"></span>
      <p class="hint neu" id="hint-moderate">Start typing to see feedback</p>
    </div>

    <div class="form-group">
      <label for="email-html5">Browser's Built-in <code>type="email"</code> (HTML5)</label>
      <input type="email" id="email-html5" placeholder="type an email…" autocomplete="off" />
      <span class="icon" id="icon-html5"></span>
      <p class="hint neu" id="hint-html5">Start typing to see feedback</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
       SECTION 2 — Test Cases
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2>🧪 Test Cases — Where Regex Breaks</h2>
    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#64748b;margin-bottom:1rem;line-height:1.5;">
      Each row shows how the <em>Simple</em> and <em>Moderate</em> regexes judge real-world addresses,
      and whether the address is <strong style="color:#f1f5f9">actually valid</strong> per RFC 5321/5322.
    </p>
    <div class="test-grid" id="test-grid">
      <span class="header">Email Address</span>
      <span class="header">Simple</span>
      <span class="header">Moderate</span>
    </div>
    <p class="scroll-note" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">↓ scroll for more ↓</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
       SECTION 3 — Why Regex Is Fundamentally Limited
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2>⚠️ Why Regex Is Fundamentally Limited</h2>

    <blockquote>
      "The syntax of an email address is more complex than most people imagine."
      <cite>— RFC 5322 §3.4.1, Internet Message Format</cite>
    </blockquote>

    <br/>

    <ul class="limitation-list">
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">📐</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>RFC 5322 is not a regular language</strong>
          <p>
            Email syntax defined in RFC 5322 includes <em>nested comments</em> like
            <code>user(this is a comment)@example.com</code>, folding whitespace, and
            quoted strings. Nested structures require a context-free grammar —
            something a finite-state regex engine <strong>cannot express</strong> by
            definition. No regex can be both complete and correct.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">🌍</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>Internationalised addresses (RFC 6531 / SMTPUTF8)</strong>
          <p>
            Unicode local parts are valid: <code>用户@例子.广告</code>,
            <code>θσερ@εχαμπλε.ψομ</code>, <code>Ñoño@example.com</code>.
            Most regexes silently reject these, excluding real users.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">🏷️</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>TLD validation is a moving target</strong>
          <p>
            ICANN has delegated over <strong>1,500 TLDs</strong> including
            <code>.museum</code>, <code>.travelersinsurance</code> (24 chars), and
            single-character IDN TLDs. Hardcoding <code>{2,6}</code> or similar
            breaks legitimate addresses.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">💬</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>Quoted local parts are valid</strong>
          <p>
            RFC 5321 allows <code>"john..doe"@example.com</code>,
            <code>"very.(),:;&lt;&gt;[]\".VERY.\"very@\\ \"very\".unusual"@strange.example.com</code>.
            These are syntactically valid but virtually every regex rejects them.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">🖥️</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>IP address literals are valid</strong>
          <p>
            <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> and <code>user@[IPv6:2001:db8::1]</code>
            are fully legal per RFC 5321 §4.1.3. Most regexes reject them outright.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">🔇</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>Syntax ≠ Deliverability</strong>
          <p>
            Even a <em>perfectly</em> spec-compliant regex can only verify
            <strong>syntax</strong>. It cannot know whether the domain has an MX
            record, whether the mailbox exists, or whether the address belongs to
            the person submitting it. Syntax is the smallest part of the problem.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="lim-icon">🤯</span>
        <div class="lim-body">
          <strong>The "complete" RFC 5322 regex is unusable</strong>
          <p>
            The closest known regex approximation of RFC 5322 is
            <strong>over 6,000 characters long</strong>, causes catastrophic
            backtracking on certain inputs (ReDoS vulnerability), and still
            doesn't cover every edge case.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <br/>
    <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:#64748b;">The regex used by most tutorials:</p>
    <div class="regex-box simple" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">/^[\w._%+\-]+@[\w.\-]+\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}$/</div>
    <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:#64748b;margin-top:0.75rem;">A closer-but-still-incomplete RFC 5322 approximation:</p>
    <div class="regex-box" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">
      /^(?:[a-zA-Z0-9!#$%&amp;'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+(?:\.[a-zA-Z0-9!#$%&amp;'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+)*|"(?:[\x01-\x08\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x1f\x21\x23-\x5b\x5d-\x7f]|\\[\x01-\x09\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x7f])*")@(?:(?:[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9])?\.)+[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9])?|\[(?:(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\.){3}(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?|[a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9]:(?:[\x01-\x08\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x1f\x21-\x5a\x53-\x7f]|\\[\x01-\x09\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x7f])+)\])$/
    </div>
    <p style="font-size:0.75rem;color:#475569;margin-top:0.5rem;">
      ↑ Still incomplete. Still vulnerable to ReDoS. Still not worth it.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
       SECTION 4 — Better Alternatives
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2>✅ Better Alternatives for Production</h2>
    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#64748b;margin-bottom:1rem;line-height:1.5;">
      Use a layered approach. No single technique is sufficient on its own.
    </p>

    <div class="alt-grid">

      <div class="alt-card">
        <div class="alt-title">Dedicated Libraries</div>
        <div class="alt-lang">JS / Node.js</div>
        <p>
          <code>validator.js</code> — <code>isEmail()</code> is battle-tested,
          handles Unicode, IP literals, and is kept up to date with RFC changes.
        </p>
        <p class="pro">✔ Easy drop-in, well maintained</p>
        <p class="con">✘ Still only syntax</p>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-card">
        <div class="alt-title">email-validator</div>
        <div class="alt-lang">Python</div>
        <p>
          <code>python-email-validator</code> parses per RFC 5322, normalises
          addresses, checks DNS MX records, and handles SMTPUTF8.
        </p>
        <p class="pro">✔ DNS check built-in</p>
        <p class="con">✘ Network I/O required</p>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-card">
        <div class="alt-title">MX Record Check</div>
        <div class="alt-lang">Server-side (any lang)</div>
        <p>
          Query DNS for the domain's MX records. Confirms the domain is
          <em>configured to receive email</em>. Catches typos like
          <code>@gmial.com</code>.
        </p>
        <p class="pro">✔ Catches bad domains</p>
        <p class="con">✘ Not mailbox-level</p>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-card">
        <div class="alt-title">Verification Email</div>
        <div class="alt-lang">UX Pattern</div>
        <p>
          Send a confirmation link or code. The <strong>only</strong> method that
          proves the address exists, is reachable, and belongs to the user.
        </p>
        <p class="pro">✔ Ground truth</p>
        <p class="con">✘ Friction for users</p>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-card">
        <div class="alt-title">SMTP Probe</div>
        <div class="alt-lang">Server-side</div>
        <p>
          Connect to the mail server and issue <code>RCPT TO</code> without
          sending. Many servers reject unknown mailboxes at this stage.
        </p>
        <p class="pro">✔ Mailbox-level check</p>
        <p class="con">✘ Many servers block this</p>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-card">
        <div class="alt-title">Commercial APIs</div>
        <div class="alt-lang">REST / any lang</div>
        <p>
          Services like <strong>ZeroBounce</strong>, <strong>Hunter.io</strong>,
          or <strong>Abstract API</strong> combine syntax, DNS, SMTP, and
          disposable-address detection.
        </p>
        <p class="pro">✔ Most comprehensive</p>
        <p class="con">✘ Cost &amp; privacy tradeoffs</p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <br/>

    <div style="background:#0f172a;border:1px solid #334155;border-radius:0.6rem;padding:1rem;">
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem;font-weight:600;color:#f1f5f9;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">
        💡 Recommended Production Strategy
      </p>
      <ol style="font-size:0.8rem;color:#94a3b8;line-height:1.8;padding-left:1.2rem;">
        <li><strong style="color:#e2e8f0">Client-side:</strong> Simple regex or <code>type="email"</code> for instant UX feedback only.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e2e8f0">Server-side:</strong> Parse with a dedicated RFC-aware library.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e2e8f0">Server-side:</strong> DNS MX lookup to validate the domain.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e2e8f0">Always:</strong> Send a verification email before granting access.</li>
        <li><strong style="color:#e2e8f0">Optional:</strong> Commercial API for high-value flows (payments, enterprise).</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <footer>
    References: RFC 5321 (SMTP), RFC 5322 (Internet Message Format), RFC 6531 (SMTPUTF8),
    RFC 5890 (IDNA). The HTML5 <code>type="email"</code> spec intentionally uses a
    "willful violation" of RFC 5322 for practical UX reasons (WHATWG Living Standard §4.10.1.1.5).
  </footer>

  <script>
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Regex Definitions
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    const SIMPLE_RE   = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
    const MODERATE_RE = /^[\w._%+\-]+@[\w.\-]+\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}$/;

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Live Validation Logic
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    function applyFeedback(inputEl, iconEl, hintEl, isValid, isEmpty) {
      inputEl.classList.remove('valid', 'invalid', 'empty');
      if (isEmpty) {
        inputEl.classList.add('empty');
        iconEl.textContent = '';
        hintEl.textContent = 'Start typing to see feedback';
        hintEl.className = 'hint neu';
        return;
      }
      if (isValid) {
        inputEl.classList.add('valid');
        iconEl.textContent = '✅';
        hintEl.textContent = 'Looks valid (syntax only — not deliverability!)';
        hintEl.className = 'hint ok';
      } else {
        inputEl.classList.add('invalid');
        iconEl.textContent = '❌';
        hintEl.textContent = 'Does not match the regex pattern';
        hintEl.className = 'hint err';
      }
    }

    function wireInput(inputId, iconId, hintId, regexOrFn) {
      const input = document.getElementById(inputId);
      const icon  = document.getElementById(iconId);
      const hint  = document.getElementById(hintId);

      const validate = (typeof regexOrFn === 'function')
        ? regexOrFn
        : (v) => regexOrFn.test(v);

      input.addEventListener('input', () => {
        const val = input.value;
        if (val === '') { applyFeedback(input, icon, hint, false, true); return; }
        applyFeedback(input, icon, hint, validate(val), false);
      });
    }

    // HTML5 type="email" uses the browser's internal algorithm
    function html5Valid(val) {
      const probe = document.createElement('input');
      probe.type  = 'email';
      probe.value = val;
      return probe.validity.valid;
    }

    wireInput('email-simple',   'icon-simple',   'hint-simple',   SIMPLE_RE);
    wireInput('email-moderate', 'icon-moderate', 'hint-moderate', MODERATE_RE);
    wireInput('email-html5',    'icon-html5',    'hint-html5',    html5Valid);

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Test Cases
    // Format: [address, rfcValid (bool), note]
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    const TEST_CASES = [
      // ── Clearly valid ──
      ['user@example.com',              true,  'Standard valid'],
      ['user.name+tag@sub.example.co.uk', true, 'Subaddress + subdomain'],
      ['x@x.io',                        true,  'Short but valid'],

      // ── Valid per RFC but regex often rejects ──
      ['"john..doe"@example.com',       true,  'Quoted local part (RFC 5321)'],
      ['"very unusual"@example.com',    true,  'Quoted with space'],
      ['user@[192.168.1.1]',            true,  'IP literal domain (RFC 5321)'],
      ['user@[IPv6:2001:db8::1]',       true,  'IPv6 literal domain'],
      ['用户@例子.广告',                  true,  'Full Unicode (RFC 6531)'],
      ['θσερ@εχαμπλε.ψομ',             true,  'Greek Unicode'],
      ['user@travelersinsurance.com',   true,  'Long TLD (24 chars)'],
      ['user@museum.example',           true,  '.museum TLD'],
      ['admin@mailserver1',             true,  'No dot in domain (RFC allows)'],

      // ── Invalid per RFC but regex often accepts ──
      ['user@',                         false, 'Missing domain'],
      ['@example.com',                  false, 'Missing local part'],
      ['user@.example.com',             false, 'Domain starts with dot'],
      ['user..name@example.com',        false, 'Consecutive dots (unquoted)'],
      ['user@example..com',             false, 'Consecutive dots in domain'],
      ['user @example.com',             false, 'Space in local part'],
      ['user@exam ple.com',             false, 'Space in domain'],
      ['.user@example.com',             false, 'Leading dot in local part'],
      ['user.@example.com',             false, 'Trailing dot in local part'],

      // ── Tricky edge cases ──
      ['plainaddress',                  false, 'No @ at all'],
      ['user@com',                      false, 'TLD only domain (debatable)'],
      ['a@b.c',                         true,  'Minimal valid (single-char TLD)'],
      ['user@-example.com',             false, 'Domain starts with hyphen'],
      ['user@example-.com',             false, 'Domain ends with hyphen'],
    ];

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Render test grid
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    function badgeFor(regexResult, rfcValid) {
      if (regexResult === rfcValid) {
        return `<span class="badge pass">✓ correct</span>`;
      }
      if (regexResult && !rfcValid) {
        return `<span class="badge warn">⚠ false +</span>`;
      }
      return `<span class="badge fail">✗ false −</span>`;
    }

    const grid = document.getElementById('test-grid');

    TEST_CASES.forEach(([email, rfcValid, note]) => {
      const simpleResult   = SIMPLE_RE.test(email);
      const moderateResult = MODERATE_RE.test(email);

      const emailCell = document.createElement('div');
      emailCell.className = 'email-cell';
      emailCell.innerHTML = `
        ${escHtml(email)}
        <br/>
        <span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.7rem;color:#475569;">${escHtml(note)}</span>
        <span class="badge ${rfcValid ? 'valid' : 'fail'}" style="margin-left:0.3rem;font-size:0.65rem;">
          RFC: ${rfcValid ? 'valid' : 'invalid'}
        </span>
      `;

      const simpleCell   = document.createElement('div');
      simpleCell.innerHTML = badgeFor(simpleResult, rfcValid);

      const moderateCell = document.createElement('div');
      moderateCell.innerHTML = badgeFor(moderateResult, rfcValid);

      grid.appendChild(emailCell);
      grid.appendChild(simpleCell);
      grid.appendChild(moderateCell);
    });

    function escHtml(str) {
      return str
        .replace(/&/g, '&amp;')
        .replace(/</g, '&lt;')
        .replace(/>/g, '&gt;')
        .replace(/"/g, '&quot;');
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## What's inside and why each decision was made

| Section | What it does | Key design choice |
|---|---|---|
| **Live inputs** | Three inputs, each using a different validation strategy | Lets you *feel* the difference in real time |
| **Simple regex** | `/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/` | Intentionally permissive to show false positives |
| **Moderate regex** | `/^[\w._%+\-]+@[\w.\-]+\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}$/` | The "standard" tutorial regex — still wrong |
| **HTML5 type=email** | Browser's built-in algorithm via `validity.valid` | A WHATWG "willful violation" of RFC 5322 — pragmatic but incomplete |
| **Test case grid** | 25 addresses with RFC ground truth | Badges show ✓ correct, ⚠ false positive, ✗ false negative |
| **Limitations section** | 7 fundamental reasons regex fails | Grounded in RFC 5321/5322/6531 citations |
| **Alternatives section** | 6 production strategies with pros/cons | Layered approach recommended |

The core honest takeaway: **use regex only as a first-pass UX hint, never as a security or correctness gate**, and always verify via a confirmation email.

