  <div class="limitations-card">
    <h2>⚠️ Why Regex Is Fundamentally Limited</h2>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>1 · RFC 5321 / 5322 allow quoted local parts</h3>
      <p>
        Addresses like <code>"john doe"@example.com</code> or
        <code>"very.unusual.@.unusual.com"@example.com</code> are
        <em>completely valid</em> per RFC 5321 §4.1.2. Almost every
        regex silently rejects them.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>2 · Comments are legal inside addresses</h3>
      <p>
        <code>john(comment)@example.com</code> and
        <code>john@(comment)example.com</code> are both RFC-legal.
        A regex that accepts them would also accept garbage.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>3 · IP address literals as domain</h3>
      <p>
        <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> and
        <code>user@[IPv6:2001:db8::1]</code> are valid mail destinations.
        Matching IPv6 correctly with regex is notoriously error-prone.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>4 · Internationalised addresses (RFC 6531)</h3>
      <p>
        <code>用户@例子.广告</code> or <code>josé@domínio.pt</code>
        are valid SMTPUTF8 addresses. Unicode-aware regex is
        possible but fragile and rarely implemented correctly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>5 · TLD existence is unknowable at parse time</h3>
      <p>
        <code>user@example.invalidtld</code> passes every regex but
        will bounce. ICANN adds new TLDs regularly; a hardcoded
        regex list is always out of date.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>6 · DNS MX records cannot be checked client-side</h3>
      <p>
        Even a perfectly formatted address fails if the domain has
        no MX record. Only a server-side DNS lookup can catch this.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="limit-item">
      <h3>7 · Mailbox existence requires SMTP</h3>
      <p>
        <code>definitely-not-real-9999@gmail.com</code> passes every
        format check. Only an SMTP handshake (or a verification
        service) can confirm the mailbox exists.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rfc-note">
      📄 <strong>The gold-standard RFC 5322 regex</strong> (by Dominic Sayers) is
      over <strong>6 000 characters</strong> long and still does not cover every
      edge case. The IETF itself notes in RFC 3696 §3 that
      "attempts to validate email addresses with regular expressions
      are doomed to failure." The only true validation is
      <strong>sending a message and confirming receipt</strong>.
    </div>
  </div>

