<body>

<div class="container">

    <h1>📧 Real-Time Email Validation</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Regex-powered client-side validation — with an honest look at its limits</p>

    <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════
         VALIDATOR CARD
    ════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="card">
        <h2><span class="icon">✏️</span> Try It Live</h2>

        <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input
                type="text"
                id="emailInput"
                class="email-input"
                placeholder="you@example.com"
                autocomplete="off"
                spellcheck="false"
            />
            <span class="status-icon" id="statusIcon"></span>
        </div>

        <div class="status-message neutral" id="statusMessage">
            Start typing to validate your email address…
        </div>

        <!-- Breakdown -->
        <div class="breakdown">
            <h3>Address Breakdown</h3>
            <div class="parts">
                <div class="part">
                    <span class="part-label">Local Part</span>
                    <span class="part-value highlight-neutral" id="partLocal">—</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arrow">@</div>
                <div class="part">
                    <span class="part-label">Domain</span>
                    <span class="part-value highlight-neutral" id="partDomain">—</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arrow">.</div>
                <div class="part">
                    <span class="part-label">TLD</span>
                    <span class="part-value highlight-neutral" id="partTLD">—</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Regex display -->
        <div class="regex-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
            <div class="label">Regex Pattern Used</div>
            <code id="regexDisplay">/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]{2,}$/</code>
        </div>

        <!-- Example addresses -->
        <div class="examples">
            <h3>Click to Test Examples</h3>
            <div class="example-grid" id="exampleGrid"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════
         LIMITATIONS CARD
    ════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="limitations-card">
        <h2><span>⚠️</span> Why Regex Can't Fully Validate Email Addresses</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
            The RFC 5321 and RFC 5322 specifications define email addresses with a complexity that
            makes them practically impossible to validate completely with a regular expression.
            Even the official RFC 5322 regex spans <strong>thousands of characters</strong> and
            still cannot verify the most important thing: <em>does this mailbox actually exist?</em>
        </p>

        <div class="limitation-item">
            <div class="num">1</div>
            <div class="content">
                <h4>RFC-Valid Formats That Regex Routinely Rejects</h4>
                <p>
                    Many unusual but perfectly legal email formats confuse simple regex patterns.
                    Quoted local parts like <span class="rfc-example">"john doe"@example.com</span>,
                    IP-address domains like <span class="rfc-example">user@[192.168.1.1]</span>,
                    and comments like <span class="rfc-example">(comment)user@example.com</span>
                    are all valid per RFC 5321 but fail most regex validators.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="limitation-item">
            <div class="num">2</div>
            <div class="content">
                <h4>Regex Cannot Verify Domain Existence</h4>
                <p>
                    A regex will happily accept <span class="rfc-example">user@totallymadeupdomain12345.xyz</span>
                    because the format looks correct. It has no way to check whether
                    the domain has valid DNS records (MX, A, or AAAA) that prove mail
                    can actually be delivered there.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="limitation-item">
            <div class="num">3</div>
            <div class="content">
                <h4>Regex Cannot Verify Mailbox Existence</h4>
                <p>
                    Even if the domain is real, <span class="rfc-example">definitelynotreal999@gmail.com</span>
                    passes regex validation. Only an SMTP handshake (or a verification
                    service) can confirm that the specific mailbox exists on the mail
                    server and is accepting messages.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="limitation-item">
            <div class="num">4</div>
            <div class="content">
                <h4>Internationalised Email Addresses (SMTPUTF8)</h4>
                <p>
                    RFC 6531 allows Unicode characters in both the local part and domain:
                    <span class="rfc-example">用户@例子.广告</span> and
                    <span class="rfc-example">θσερ@εχαμπλε.ψομ</span> are valid addresses.
                    ASCII-only regex patterns reject them entirely, blocking real users.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="limitation-item">
            <div class="num">5</div>
            <div class="content">
                <h4>New gTLDs Break Naive TLD Rules</h4>
                <p>
                    Patterns that restrict TLDs to 2–6 characters will reject valid
                    modern addresses like <span class="rfc-example">user@example.museum</span>,
                    <span class="rfc-example">user@example.photography</span>, or
                    <span class="rfc-example">user@example.international</span>.
                    ICANN continues to add new TLDs regularly.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="limitation-item">
            <div class="num">6</div>
            <div class="content">
                <h4>Regex Complexity vs. Correctness Trade-off</h4>
                <p>
                    The fully RFC-compliant regex is so complex it becomes unmaintainable
                    and introduces its own bugs. Simpler regex patterns (like the one above)
                    are pragmatic but will both <em>false-positive</em> (accept bad addresses)
                    and <em>false-negative</em> (reject good ones). There is no sweet spot.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════
         ALTERNATIVES CARD
    ════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="alternatives-card">
        <h2><span>🚀</span> Better Alternatives for Production Use</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
            In real applications, combine lightweight format checking with one or more
            of the following strategies to achieve genuinely reliable email validation.
        </p>

        <div class="alt-grid">

            <div class="alt-item">
                <div class="alt-header">
                    <span class="alt-icon">📨</span>
                    <h4>Confirmation Email (Double Opt-In)</h4>
                    <span class="alt-badge badge-best">Best</span>
                </div>
                <p>
                    Send a confirmation link or one-time code to the address. If the user
                    clicks it, you have <strong>proof the address exists and is controlled
                    by them</strong>. This is the gold standard for registration flows and
                    cannot be faked.
                </p>
                <div class="code-snippet">// Server sends:
POST /send-confirmation
{ email: "user@example.com" }

// User clicks link → address confirmed ✓</div>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <div class="alt-header">
                    <span class="alt-icon">🌐</span>
                    <h4>DNS / MX Record Lookup</h4>
                    <span class="alt-badge badge-good">Good</span>
                </div>
                <p>
                    After basic format validation, resolve the domain's MX (Mail Exchanger)
                    DNS records server-side. If no MX records exist, the domain cannot
                    receive email — reject it early without sending anything.
                </p>
                <div class="code-snippet">// Node.js example
const dns = require('dns').promises;
const records = await dns.resolveMx('example.com');
// records = [{ exchange, priority }]
// Empty array → no mail server exists</div>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <div class="alt-header">
                    <span class="alt-icon">🔌</span>
                    <h4>Email Verification API</h4>
                    <span class="alt-badge badge-good">Good</span>
                </div>
                <p>
                    Services like <strong>ZeroBounce</strong>, <strong>NeverBounce</strong>,
                    <strong>Mailgun Validation</strong>, and <strong>Abstract API</strong>
                    perform DNS checks, SMTP handshakes, disposable-address detection, and
                    typo correction in a single API call.
                </p>
                <div class="code-snippet">// Abstract API example
GET https://emailvalidation.abstractapi.com/v1/
  ?api_key=YOUR_KEY
  &email=user@example.com

// Returns: deliverability, MX found,
// is_disposable, is_role, did_you_mean…</div>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <div class="alt-header">
                    <span class="alt-icon">📚</span>
                    <h4>Battle-Tested Libraries</h4>
                    <span class="alt-badge badge-good">Good</span>
