      <p class="section-title">❌ Core Limitations of Regex Validation</p>
      <div class="limit-list">

        <div class="limit-item">
          <strong>1. Quoted strings in local parts are valid</strong>
          <p>
            RFC 5321 allows quoted strings: <code>"john doe"@example.com</code> and
            <code>"very.unusual.@.unusual.com"@example.com</code> are both technically valid.
            Most regex patterns reject these entirely.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="limit-item">
          <strong>2. IP address literals as domains</strong>
          <p>
            Addresses like <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> and <code>user@[IPv6:::1]</code>
            are valid per RFC 5321. Regex patterns almost never handle bracket-enclosed
            IP literals correctly.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="limit-item">
          <strong>3. Comments are syntactically valid</strong>
          <p>
            <code>(comment)user@example.com</code> and <code>user@example(comment).com</code>
            are valid per RFC 5322. No common regex accounts for this, and they
            would incorrectly reject such addresses.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="limit-item">
          <strong>4. Internationalized email addresses (EAI)</strong>
          <p>
            RFC 6531 extended SMTP to support Unicode. Addresses like
            <code>用户@例子.广告</code> or <code>Ñoño@español.es</code> are valid
            in modern systems. ASCII-only regex patterns will always reject them.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="limit-item">
          <strong>5. Regex cannot verify deliverability</strong>
          <p>
            Even a perfect regex can only check <em>format</em>. It cannot know whether
            the domain has valid MX records, whether the mailbox exists, or whether
            the address is a temporary/disposable one. <code>fake@real-domain.com</code>
            will always pass regex.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="limit-item">
          <strong>6. New TLDs and edge-case domains</strong>
          <p>
            TLDs like <code>.museum</code>, <code>.cancerresearch</code>, or single-label
            domains on private networks (<code>user@localhost</code>) are valid in specific
            contexts but often rejected by regex patterns with rigid TLD length rules.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
