  <h1>📧 Email Validation <span>Deep Dive</span></h1>

  <!-- ── Validation Form Card ── -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2>🔬 Live Regex Validator</h2>

    <form id="emailForm" novalidate>
      <div class="form-group">
        <label for="emailInput">Email Address</label>
        <div class="input-wrapper">
          <input
            type="email"
            id="emailInput"
            name="email"
            placeholder="you@example.com"
            autocomplete="off"
            spellcheck="false"
            class="pristine"
          />
          <span class="status-icon" id="statusIcon"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="feedback pristine" id="feedbackMsg">Enter an email address to validate</span>
      </div>

      <button type="submit" id="submitBtn" disabled>Submit</button>
    </form>

    <!-- Regex used -->
    <div style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:0.8rem; color:#64748b; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">
        🔍 Regex pattern in use (RFC 5322 simplified):
      </p>
      <div class="regex-display" id="regexDisplay"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Try These Examples ── -->
  <div class="card" style="max-width:520px;">
    <h2>🧪 Click to Test Examples</h2>

    <p style="font-size:0.82rem; color:#64748b; margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
      Click any chip to populate the input and see validation in action.
    </p>

    <p class="chip-label">✅ Regex considers VALID:</p>
    <div class="example-chips" id="validChips"></div>

    <p class="chip-label" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">❌ Regex considers INVALID:</p>
    <div class="example-chips" id="invalidChips"></div>

    <p class="chip-label" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
      ⚠️ Tricky — regex says VALID but may not be real:
    </p>
    <div class="example-chips" id="trickyChips"></div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Explanation Section ── -->
  <div class="explanation">
    <h2>⚠️ Why Regex Email Validation Is Fundamentally Limited</h2>

    <!-- Limitation 1 -->
    <div class="section-block warning">
      <h3>📜 RFC 5321 / 5322 Complexity</h3>
      <p>
        The full RFC 5322 specification for valid email addresses is extraordinarily complex.
        A truly compliant regex runs to <strong>over 6,000 characters</strong>. The simplified
        patterns used in practice accept or reject addresses incorrectly because they cannot
        faithfully model the full grammar, which includes:
      </p>
      <ul style="margin-top:0.6rem;">
        <li>Quoted strings in the local part: <code>"john..doe"@example.com</code></li>
        <li>Comments: <code>john(comment)@example.com</code></li>
        <li>IP address literals: <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code></li>
        <li>Folding whitespace and obsolete syntax still in use</li>
        <li>Internationalized domain names (IDN / Punycode)</li>
        <li>Unicode local parts (SMTPUTF8): <code>用户@例子.广告</code></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Limitation 2 -->
    <div class="section-block warning">
      <h3>🌐 Domain Existence Cannot Be Verified</h3>
      <p>
        A regex can verify <em>format</em> only — it cannot know whether a domain
        actually exists, has valid <strong>MX records</strong>, or whether the
        mailbox is active. For example:
      </p>
      <ul style="margin-top:0.6rem;">
        <li><code>user@thisdoesnotexist12345.com</code> — passes any regex</li>
        <li><code>nobody@fakeTLD.invalidxyz</code> — may pass depending on the pattern</li>
        <li>New TLDs like <code>.photography</code>, <code>.museum</code> break naive patterns</li>
        <li>Single-label domains are valid on private networks but look wrong to regex</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Limitation 3 -->
    <div class="section-block warning">
      <h3>🔄 False Positives &amp; False Negatives</h3>
      <p>
        Every simplified regex trades false positives for false negatives and vice versa.
        No single regex can be both fully permissive (per RFC) and fully restrictive
        (blocking all invalid addresses):
      </p>
      <ul style="margin-top:0.6rem;">
        <li>
          <strong>False positive:</strong> <code>fake@fake</code> may pass a loose
          pattern but is not a deliverable internet address.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>False negative:</strong> <code>"very.unusual.@.unusual.com"@example.com</code>
          is RFC-valid but rejected by almost every regex.
        </li>
        <li>
          Blocking valid addresses frustrates real users and loses sign-ups.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Limitation 4 -->
    <div class="section-block warning">
      <h3>🔒 Security Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        Complex regex patterns on untrusted input can be exploited via
        <strong>ReDoS (Regular Expression Denial of Service)</strong> — crafted
        inputs cause catastrophic backtracking, consuming CPU and hanging servers.
        Always apply input length limits and use regex engines with linear-time
        guarantees for server-side validation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Better Approaches -->
    <div class="section-block success">
      <h3>✅ Better Approaches for Production</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
        Use a layered strategy — no single technique is sufficient on its own:
      </p>
      <div class="alternatives-grid">

        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>1. Minimal Format Check</h4>
          <p>
            Use a simple regex only to catch obvious typos (missing <code>@</code>,
            no domain). Keep it permissive. This is a UX hint, not a security gate.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>2. DNS / MX Lookup</h4>
          <p>
            Server-side: resolve the domain's MX records. If none exist, the address
            cannot receive mail. Eliminates fake domains instantly.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>3. Email Verification API</h4>
          <p>
            Services like <strong>ZeroBounce</strong>, <strong>NeverBounce</strong>,
            or <strong>Hunter.io</strong> perform SMTP handshake checks without
            sending a message, verifying mailbox existence.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>4. Confirmation Email</h4>
          <p>
            The only <em>definitive</em> proof: send a tokenised link to the address.
            If the user clicks it, the address is real, deliverable, and owned by them.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>5. Battle-Tested Libraries</h4>
          <p>
            Use <code>email-validator</code> (Node), <code>validate_email</code>
            (Python), or <code>egulias/email-validator</code> (PHP) — they implement
            RFC parsing far more accurately than hand-rolled regex.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>6. HTML5 Built-in</h4>
          <p>
            <code>&lt;input type="email"&gt;</code> provides browser-native
            validation per the WHATWG "valid email address" definition — a
            reasonable, well-maintained baseline for client-side UX.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Summary -->
    <div class="section-block info">
      <h3>💡 Recommended Production Strategy</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Client-side:</strong> Permissive regex or <code>type="email"</code>
        for instant UX feedback → catches obvious typos only.<br /><br />
        <strong>Server-side:</strong> RFC-compliant library validation + MX record
        check → ensures domain can receive mail.<br /><br />
        <strong>Asynchronous:</strong> Confirmation email with expiring token →
        the only true proof of ownership and deliverability.<br /><br />
        Never rely solely on regex to gate access or make security decisions based
        on email format alone.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <footer>
    Built as an educational demo &mdash; references:
    <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5321" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RFC 5321</a>,
    <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5322" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RFC 5322</a>,
    <a href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/input.html#valid-e-mail-address" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WHATWG Email Spec</a>
  </footer>

  <div id="toast">✅ Form submitted successfully!</div>

<script>
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  // Regex: A pragmatic simplified pattern.
  // Based loosely on RFC 5322 simplified form.
  // Intentionally NOT fully RFC-compliant —
  // that is the entire point of this demo.
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  const EMAIL_REGEX = /^(?:[a-zA-Z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+(?:\.[a-zA-Z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+)*|"(?:[\x01-\x08\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x1f\x21\x23-\x5b\x5d-\x7f]|\\[\x01-\x09\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x7f])*")@(?:(?:[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]{0,61}[a-zA-Z0-9])?\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}|\[(?:(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\.){3}(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?|[a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9]:(?:[\x01-\x08\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x1f\x21-\x5a\x53-\x7f]|\\[\x01-\x09\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x7f])+)\])$/;

  // Display the regex
  document.getElementById('regexDisplay').textContent = EMAIL_REGEX.toString();

  // ── DOM refs ──
  const input      = document.getElementById('emailInput');
  const feedback   = document.getElementById('feedbackMsg');
  const statusIcon = document.getElementById('statusIcon');
  const submitBtn  = document.getElementById('submitBtn');
  const toast      = document.getElementById('toast');

  // ── Example data ──
  const validExamples = [
    'user@example.com',
    'firstname.lastname@domain.org',
    'user+tag@sub.domain.co.uk',
    'x@y.io',
    'admin@mail.museum',
    'user@192.168.1.1',   // IP literal — regex handles this
  ];

  const invalidExamples = [
    'notanemail',
    '@nodomain.com',
    'missingat.com',
    'two@@at.com',
    'trailing@dot.',
    'space in@email.com',
  ];

  // These PASS the regex but are not reliably deliverable
  const trickyExamples = [
    'fake@thisdoesnotexist99999.xyz',
    'a@b.c',                          // Too-short TLD passes some patterns
    'user@-invaliddomain.com',        // Leading hyphen (actually caught by our regex)
    '"quoted local"@example.com',     // RFC-valid quoted local part
  ];

  // ── Render chips ──
  function renderChips(containerId, examples, cssClass) {
    const container = document.getElementById(containerId);
    examples.forEach(email => {
      const chip = document.createElement('button');
      chip.type = 'button';
      chip.className = `chip ${cssClass}`;
      chip.textContent = email;
      chip.addEventListener('click', () => {
        input.value = email;
        input.dispatchEvent(new Event('input'));
        input.focus();
      });
      container.appendChild(chip);
    });
  }

  renderChips('validChips',   validExamples,   'valid-example');
  renderChips('invalidChips', invalidExamples, 'invalid-example');
  renderChips('trickyChips',  trickyExamples,  'tricky-example');

  // ── Validation logic ──
  function validate(value) {
    if (value.length === 0) return 'empty';
    return EMAIL_REGEX.test(value) ? 'valid' : 'invalid';
  }

  const messages = {
    empty:   { text: 'Enter an email address to validate', icon: '' },
    valid:   { text: '✔ Looks good — format matches the regex pattern', icon: '✅' },
    invalid: { text: '✖ Invalid format — check for missing @, domain, or illegal characters', icon: '❌' },
  };

  function updateUI(state) {
    // Input border
    input.className = state === 'empty' ? 'pristine' : state;

    // Feedback text
    feedback.className = `feedback ${state === 'empty' ? 'pristine' : state}`;
    feedback.textContent = messages[state].text;

    // Icon
    statusIcon.textContent = messages[state].icon;

    // Submit button
    submitBtn.disabled = state !== 'valid';
  }

  // ── Event listeners ──
  input.addEventListener('input', () => {
    updateUI(validate(input.value.trim()));
  });

  // Show toast on submit
  document.getElementById('emailForm').addEventListener('submit', e => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (validate(input.value.trim()) !== 'valid') return;

    toast.classList.add('show');
    setTimeout(() => toast.classList.remove('show'), 3000);
  });

  // Initialise
  updateUI('empty');
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

## What This File Includes

### 🔬 The Validator
- **Real-time feedback** on every keystroke via the `input` event
- **Green border + ✅ icon** for regex-valid format
- **Red border + ❌ icon** for invalid format
- The exact regex pattern is displayed on screen so it's fully transparent
- Submit button is disabled until the format is valid

### 🧪 Interactive Examples
Clickable chips in three categories:
- **Green** — addresses the regex accepts
- **Red** — addresses the regex rejects
- **Yellow** — addresses the regex *passes* but that may not be real/deliverable (the core lesson)

### 📖 Explanation Section Covers
| Topic | Detail |
|---|---|
| RFC 5321/5322 complexity | Quoted strings, comments, IP literals, Unicode |
| Domain existence | Regex can't check MX records or if a domain is real |
| False positives/negatives | Inherent tradeoffs in any simplified pattern |
| ReDoS security risk | Catastrophic backtracking on crafted inputs |
| 6 better alternatives | From DNS lookups to confirmation emails to libraries |

