  <!-- ══════════════ LIMITATIONS CARD ══════════════ -->
  <div class="limitations">
    <div class="section-title">⚠️ Why Regex Cannot Fully Validate Emails</div>

    <ul class="limitation-list">
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">📜</span>
        <span>
          <strong>RFC 5321 &amp; 5322 are enormous.</strong> The full specification
          for valid email addresses spans hundreds of rules covering quoted strings,
          comments, folding whitespace, and obsolete syntax. A regex that covers
          all of them becomes thousands of characters long and nearly unmaintainable.
        </span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">💬</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Comments are legal.</strong> Addresses like
          <code>user(comment)@example.com</code> and
          <code>(comment)user@example.com</code> are technically valid per RFC 5322,
          but almost no regex handles them correctly.
        </span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">🔤</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Quoted local parts.</strong> <code>"user name"@example.com</code>
          and <code>"very.unusual.@.unusual.com"@example.com</code> are both valid.
          Regex struggles to correctly parse the quoting rules.
        </span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">🌍</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Internationalised addresses (RFC 6531).</strong> Unicode characters
          in the local part — e.g. <code>用户@例子.广告</code> — are valid but
          break ASCII-only patterns entirely.
        </span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">🌐</span>
        <span>
          <strong>New TLDs &amp; IP literals.</strong> Domains like
          <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> (IP literal) or addresses ending in
          <code>.photography</code> may be rejected by overly strict patterns
          that hard-code TLD lengths.
        </span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">❓</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Existence cannot be proven.</strong> Even a perfectly formatted
          address like <code>nobody@real-domain.com</code> may not exist. Regex
          can only check <em>shape</em>, never <em>deliverability</em>.
        </span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="bullet">🔄</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Regex is not context-free.</strong> Email syntax has nested
          structures (e.g. nested comments) that are context-free by nature and
          provably cannot be captured by a regular expression.
        </span>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="rfc-note">
      💡 <strong>RFC 5322 §3.4.1</strong> defines the formal grammar for email
