  <div class="card">
    <h2>
      <span class="icon icon-amber">⚠️</span>
      Why Regex Cannot Fully Validate Emails (RFC 5321 / 5322)
    </h2>

    <div class="rfc-note">
      <strong>RFC 5321</strong> (SMTP) and <strong>RFC 5322</strong> (Internet Message Format)
      define the complete specification for valid email addresses. The full grammar is
      <em>context-sensitive</em> and recursive — something regular expressions fundamentally
      cannot express. Below are concrete examples that break most regex validators.
    </div>

    <div class="limitations-grid">

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">💬 Quoted Strings</div>
        <p>
          <code>"john doe"@example.com</code> is <strong>valid</strong> per RFC 5321.
          Spaces and special characters are allowed inside double quotes in the local part.
          Most regex patterns reject this.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">🔲 IP Address Domains</div>
        <p>
          <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> and
          <code>user@[IPv6:::1]</code> are valid SMTP destinations.
          Regex can match these but validating the IP range correctly requires extra logic.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">🌍 Internationalised (IDN)</div>
        <p>
          Unicode addresses like <code>用户@例子.广告</code> are valid under
          RFC 6530 (EAI). Standard ASCII regex patterns will reject all non-ASCII characters.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">📏 Length Limits</div>
        <p>
          RFC 5321 mandates: local part ≤ 64 chars, domain ≤ 255 chars, total ≤ 320 chars.
          Regex can check these with lookaheads, but it becomes brittle and unreadable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">🔗 Comments</div>
        <p>
          <code>(comment)user@example.com</code> is technically valid per RFC 5322.
          Comments can appear before or after the local part or domain — impossible
          to handle cleanly with regex.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">🌐 DNS Does Not Exist</div>
        <p>
          <code>user@totally-fake-domain-xyz.com</code> passes every regex check but
          the domain may not exist or have no MX record. Regex has zero awareness of DNS.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">📬 Mailbox May Not Exist</div>
        <p>
          Even a perfectly formatted address pointing to a real domain
          (e.g. <code>nobody12345@gmail.com</code>) may not have an active inbox.
          Only sending a message can confirm delivery.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="limit-card">
        <div class="limit-title">🔄 New TLDs</div>
        <p>
          ICANN continuously adds new TLDs (<code>.photography</code>, <code>.xn--p1ai</code>).
          Hardcoding TLD patterns in regex quickly becomes outdated and blocks valid addresses.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

