            This is the <em>only</em> method that truly confirms an address is real,
            reachable, and belongs to the user. Used by virtually every major platform.
          </p>
          <span class="tag tag-best">⭐ Gold Standard</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-item">
        <div class="alt-number">2</div>
        <div class="alt-content">
          <h4>DNS / MX Record Lookup (Server-Side)</h4>
          <p>
            Query DNS to confirm the domain exists and has a Mail Exchanger (MX) record.
            Eliminates fake domains without sending any email. Available in all major
            backend languages: Node.js <code>dns.resolveMx()</code>, Python
            <code>dnspython</code>, PHP <code>checkdnsrr()</code>.
          </p>
          <span class="tag tag-good">🔍 Good Server-Side Check</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-item">
        <div class="alt-number">3</div>
        <div class="alt-content">
          <h4>HTML5 Built-in Input Validation</h4>
          <p>
            Use <code>&lt;input type="email"&gt;</code>. Browsers apply their own
            RFC-aware heuristic validation and surface native UI error messages.
            Not bullet-proof, but zero-cost and accessible. Combine with
            <code>required</code> and <code>pattern</code> attributes for extra control.
          </p>
          <span class="tag tag-builtin">🌐 Native Browser</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alt-item">
        <div class="alt-number">4</div>
        <div class="alt-content">
          <h4>Dedicated Validation Libraries</h4>
          <p>
            Libraries like <strong>validator.js</strong> (<code>isEmail()</code>),
            <strong>email-validator</strong> (npm), or Python's
            <strong>email-validator</strong> package implement far more complete
            RFC checks, Unicode support, and length constraints than hand-rolled regex.
          </p>
          <span class="tag tag-good">📦 Recommended Library</span>
