## Why Regex Is Fundamentally Broken for Email Validation

### The Core Problem in One Sentence

> Regex validates **syntax patterns**. Email validity requires **semantic rules, external state, and network knowledge** — none of which regex can access.

---

### RFC 5321 / 5322: The Actual Rules Nobody Reads

The email specifications are far more permissive than developers assume.

**Legal local parts (the bit before `@`) include:**

```
"john doe"@example.com          ← spaces inside quotes: VALID
"@"@example.com                 ← literal @ inside quotes: VALID
john..doe@example.com           ← consecutive dots inside quotes: VALID
user+tag@example.com            ← plus addressing: VALID
!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~@example.com ← all of these special chars: VALID
```

**Legal domain parts include:**

```
user@[192.168.1.1]              ← IPv4 literal: VALID
user@[IPv6:2001:db8::1]         ← IPv6 literal: VALID
user@例子.com                   ← Internationalised domain: VALID
用户@example.com                ← Unicode local part (RFC 6531): VALID
```

Any regex that rejects these is **wrong by specification**.

---

### The Six Specific Ways Regex Fails

| Problem | Why Regex Can't Fix It |
|---|---|
| **Quoted local parts** | Regex can't properly handle escaped characters inside arbitrary quoted strings without becoming a full parser |
| **RFC comments** like `user(note)@host.com` | Requires recursive/nested matching — not possible in most regex flavors |
| **Unicode / IDN** | ASCII-range regex rejects billions of valid international addresses by design |
| **IP address literals** | Domain validation logic is too complex for a single pattern |
| **TLD length** | ICANN allows up to 63 chars; hardcoded limits like `{2,6}` are just wrong |
| **Domain existence** | A string pattern cannot query DNS. This requires a network call. Full stop. |

---

### The ReDoS Problem (Bonus Security Flaw)

Complex email regexes are vulnerable to **Regular Expression Denial of Service**. Input like:

```
aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa@
```

Can cause **catastrophic backtracking** in poorly written regexes, consuming 100% CPU and hanging your server. This is a real, documented attack class.

---

### What You Should Actually Do

**Tier 1 — Always do this, no exceptions:**
- Send a **verification email with a tokenized link**. This is the only proof the address exists AND the user controls it.

**Tier 2 — Server-side sanity check:**
- DNS **MX record lookup** on the domain. Eliminates fake domains immediately. Zero false positives.
- Use a **maintained library** (`python-email-validator`, `email-validator` on npm) rather than a handwritten regex.

**Tier 3 — For high-value flows (signups, billing):**
- Use a **deliverability API** (ZeroBounce, Hunter, AbstractAPI). They detect disposable addresses, catch-all servers, and known-bad domains.

**For basic UI feedback only:**
- Use `<input type="email">` — the browser's built-in check is a reasonable sanity check, handles common cases, and you wrote zero regex.
- If you must use regex, use the [HTML5 spec's own pattern](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/input.html#valid-e-mail-address) and **acknowledge it is not RFC-complete**.

---

### The One-Line Summary

```
Regex: "Does this string look like an email?"  ← Wrong question
Truth: "Can I send mail to this address?"      ← Requires DNS + SMTP + verification email
```

No amount of regex cleverness bridges that gap.

