                    These implement the actual RFC grammar properly.
                </span>
            </div>
            <div class="alt-item">
                <span class="num">05</span>
                <span class="desc">
                    <strong>Email verification APIs.</strong> Services like <strong>ZeroBounce</strong>,
                    <strong>Hunter.io</strong>, <strong>Kickbox</strong>, or <strong>Abstract API</strong>
                    do MX checks, SMTP probing, disposable email detection, and typo correction.
                </span>
            </div>
            <div class="alt-item">
                <span class="num">06</span>
                <span class="desc">
                    <strong>Browser's built-in <code>type="email"</code>.</strong> If you must do client-side
                    checks, the browser's native validation is at least as good as your regex and requires
                    zero code. That's what this demo uses on the input element itself.
                </span>
            </div>
            <div class="alt-item">
                <span class="num">07</span>
                <span class="desc">
                    <strong>Minimal sanity check only.</strong> If you insist on regex, use only
                    <code>/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/</code> — a humble check for obvious garbage.
                    Make no claims beyond that. Don't reject valid addresses with complex local parts.
                </span>
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>

    <script>
        // A reasonably thorough regex — still fundamentally incomplete per RFC 5321/5322
        // It will reject valid addresses and potentially accept invalid ones at edge cases.
        const EMAIL_REGEX = /^(?:[a-zA-Z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+(?:\.[a-zA-Z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+)*|"(?:[\x01-\x08\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x1f\x21\x23-\x5b\x5d-\x7f]|\\[\x01-\x09\x0b\x0c\x0e-\x7f])*")@(?:(?:[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9])?\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}|(?:\[(?:(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\.){3}(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\]))$/;

        document.getElementById('regexDisplay').textContent = EMAIL_REGEX.toString();

        const input = document.getElementById('emailInput');
        const feedback = document.getElementById('feedback');

        function validate(value) {
            if (value.length === 0) {
                return { state: 'neutral', message: '' };
            }
            if (EMAIL_REGEX.test(value)) {
                return {
                    state: 'valid',
                    message: '✓ Passes regex — but this proves nothing about deliverability.'
                };
            } else {
                return {
                    state: 'invalid',
                    message: '✗ Fails regex — though it might still be a valid RFC address.'
                };
            }
        }

        input.addEventListener('input', () => {
            const result = validate(input.value.trim());

            // Remove all state classes
            input.classList.remove('valid', 'invalid', 'neutral');
            feedback.classList.remove('valid', 'invalid', 'neutral');

            // Apply new state
            input.classList.add(result.state);
            feedback.classList.add(result.state);
            feedback.textContent = result.message || '\u200B';
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## The honest summary you already know:

| Approach | Catches typos | Proves existence | RFC complete | Correct tool |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Regex | Partially | ❌ No | ❌ No | ❌ |
| `type="email"` | Partially | ❌ No | ❌ No | ⚠ Acceptable minimum |
| MX lookup | ✅ Domain | ❌ No | N/A | ✅ |
| Confirmation email | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | N/A | ✅ Best |
| Verification API | ✅ Yes | ✅ Mostly | N/A | ✅ |

**The regex in the demo is one of the more complete ones in circulation. It still fails on internationalized addresses, certain quoted local parts, IPv6 literals, and tells you absolutely nothing about whether mail will actually be delivered.**

Use confirmation emails. Everything else is theater.
